<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch12-string-theory" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>String Theory</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Prior chapters focused on statistical analysis of tweet arrival times and built on
      earlier knowledge of samples and distributions. This chapter switches gears to focus
      on manipulating so-called <q>unstructured</q> data, which in most cases means natural
      language texts. Tweets are again a useful source of data for this because tweets are
      mainly short (140 characters or less) character strings.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-strings-overview">
    <title>Text as Data</title>

    <p>
      If you think about the Internet, and specifically about the World Wide Web for a while,
      you will realize: 1) That there are zillions of web pages; and 2) That most of the
      information on those web pages is <q>unstructured,</q> in the sense that it does not
      consist of nice rows and columns of numeric data. Instead, most of the data spread out
      across the Internet is text, digital photographs, or digital videos.
    </p>

    <p>
      Text is one of the most common forms of human communication, hence the label that
      researchers use sometimes: <term>natural language</term>. At the most basic level, we
      have a great system for representing individual characters of text inside of computers
      called <q>Unicode.</q> Unicode provides a binary representation of characters in most
      of the world's written languages, over 110,000 characters in all. Unicode supersedes
      ASCII, which was one of the most popular standards for representing characters from the
      dawn of the computer age.
    </p>

    <p>
      One of the most striking things about strings from a computer programming perspective
      is that they seem to be changing their length all the time. You can't perform the
      usual mathematical operations on character strings the way you can with numbers, but
      it is very common to <q>split</q> strings into smaller strings, and to <q>add</q>
      strings together to form longer strings.
    </p>

    <p>
      Fortunately, R has a wide range of functions for manipulating, keeping track of,
      searching, and analyzing string data. Let's begin by loading a new package called
      <c>stringr</c>. Although R has quite a few string functions in its core, they tend
      to be a bit disorganized. Hadley Wickham, a professor of statistics at Rice
      University, created this <c>stringr</c> package to make string manipulation functions
      easier to use:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-stringr">
      <code>
EnsurePackage("stringr")
tweetDF &lt;- TweetFrame("#solar", 100)
      </code>
    </program>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-string-functions">
    <title>Basic String Operations</title>

    <p>
      The first and most basic thing to do with strings is to see how long they are. The
      <c>stringr</c> package gives us the <c>str_length()</c> function:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-str-length">
      <code>
attach(tweetDF)
textlen &lt;- str_length(text)
head(textlen, 10)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      We can also look for matching text within a string using <c>str_detect()</c>, which
      returns a vector of TRUE and FALSE values. And <c>str_locate()</c> provides the
      starting and ending positions of a match within a string. The <c>str_sub()</c>
      function lets us extract a sub-string given a start and end position:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-str-detect">
      <code>
hasURL &lt;- str_detect(text, "http")
hasrt &lt;- str_detect(text, "RT ")
longtext &lt;- textlen > 140
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Search and replace operations are also very common. The <c>str_replace_all()</c>
      function from the <c>stringr</c> package finds all matches to a regular expression
      pattern and replaces them with another string:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-str-replace">
      <code>
tweets &lt;- str_replace_all(text, "@[a-z,A-Z]*", "")
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The second argument here is a <term>regular expression</term>: a powerful and compact
      language for specifying patterns in text. The regular expression <c>@[a-z,A-Z]*</c>
      matches the at sign followed by zero or more upper or lowercase letters. The asterisk
      <c>*</c> is what indicates the zero or more. That regular expression will match any
      screenname referral that appears within a tweet.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-string-tables">
    <title>Contingency Tables for String Flags</title>

    <p>
      Once we have created logical flag variables indicating interesting features of tweets
      (for example, <c>hasrt</c>, <c>longtext</c>, and <c>numurls</c>), we can use the
      <c>table()</c> function to cross-tabulate them:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-table">
      <code>
numurls &lt;- str_count(text, "http")
table(numurls, longtext)
prop.table(table(numurls, longtext))
table(numurls, hasrt, longtext)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      We can also use logical expressions inside bracket notation to compute statistics for
      specific subsets of tweets:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch12-subset-mean">
      <code>
mean(textlen[hasrt &amp; longtext])
mean(textlen[!hasrt &amp; longtext])
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Looking back over this chapter, we took a close look at some of the string
      manipulation functions provided by the <c>stringr</c> package. These included finding
      the length of a string, finding matching text within a string, doing search and
      replace operations, and cross-tabulating string features. In the next chapter we will
      tackle analyzing the actual words that appear in text documents.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch12">
    <title>Chapter Challenges</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-challenge1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Create a function that takes as input a data frame of tweets and returns as output
          a list of all of the retweet screennames. As an extra challenge, see if you can
          reduce that list of screennames to a unique set (i.e., no duplicates) while also
          generating a count of the number of times that each retweet screenname appeared.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-challenge2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Once you have written that function, copy and modify it to create a new function
          that extracts a unique list of hashtags from a data frame of tweets. Recall that
          hashtags begin with the <q>#</q> character and may contain any combination of
          upper and lowercase characters as well as digits.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

